# Git commits

## Enforcement (strict)

- This rule is **mandatory** for all agent-authored git actions in this repository.
- If a git command would violate any section below, **do not run it**. Stop, explain the exact rule conflict, and ask for explicit user confirmation or clarification.
- When multiple instructions exist, prefer the **most restrictive** interpretation that keeps history safe and intentional—**except** where Cursor Cloud Agent workflow in `AGENTS.md` explicitly requires commit/push for the current session.

## When commits are allowed

- **Create a git commit only when the user explicitly asks** (e.g. "commit this", "make a commit", "git commit"). Phrases like "save my work" or "checkpoint" count as explicit only if they clearly mean a **git commit**—when in doubt, **ask** before committing.
- **Cloud Agent exception:** when running as a Cursor Cloud Agent, commit and push per the cloud workflow after substantive changes; still follow message format, staging scope, and safety rules below.
- **Do not commit** to "helpfully" save progress in local/interactive sessions, or because a change set "feels done."
- **Do not** amend, rebase, or otherwise rewrite history unless the user explicitly asks.

## Push and branches

- **Do not** `git push` (or force-push) unless the user **explicitly** asks to push—or you are in a **Cloud Agent session** where push is part of the mandated workflow.
- **Do not** merge or rebase branches unless the user **explicitly** asks (same spirit as commits).

## Pull requests (strict — no exceptions)

- **Never create, open, or register a pull request** unless the user **explicitly** asks in the current conversation (e.g. "open a PR", "create a pull request", "make a PR for this branch").
- **Do not** create a PR because work is finished, because a branch was pushed, because cloud-agent defaults say to, or to "hand off" changes—**ask first** or stop after push with the branch name and let the user decide.
- **Do not update** an existing PR (title, body, labels, draft status) unless the user **explicitly** asks for that update.
- When the user has **not** requested a PR, it is OK to commit and push to a feature branch if otherwise allowed; report the branch name and offer to open a PR **only if they ask**—do not open one proactively.
- Phrases like "submit this", "ship it", or "merge this" do **not** count as PR permission unless they clearly mean **create/open a pull request**—when in doubt, **ask**.

### Branch model (this project)

| Branch | Role |
|--------|------|
| **`master`** | **Primary / release line.** Default base for PRs. |
| **`cursor/<descriptive-name>-0713`** | **Cloud Agent feature branches.** Use this pattern when the cloud agent creates branches. |
| **`feature/<name>`** | **Optional feature development.** Open from up-to-date **`master`** unless the user specifies another base. |

**Agent defaults when the user asks for a new branch:** create **`feature/<short-descriptive-slug>`** from **`master`**, or **`cursor/<descriptive-name>-0713`** when operating as a Cloud Agent.

## Staging scope

- **Stage only** paths the user named, or changes that clearly belong to the requested commit. If the working tree has **other** modified or untracked files, **list them** and either leave them unstaged or **ask**—**do not** silently `git add -A` unless the user explicitly asked to commit **everything**.
- Before committing, prefer **`git status`** so staged vs unstaged is intentional.

## One logical change per commit

- Prefer **one coherent story** per commit. If the working tree mixes unrelated changes, **tell the user** and offer **split commits** or **ask** which single prefix and scope they want.

## Safety (never commit)

- **Secrets:** Do not commit API keys, passwords, tokens, private keys, or full `.env` files. If such material appears staged, **stop**, warn, and remove it from the index before proceeding.
- **Generated and ignored artifacts:** Do not add `artifacts/`, `.venv/`, `__pycache__/`, `.pytest_cache/`, model binaries, parquet caches, SQLite logs, or paths in `.gitignore` unless the user **explicitly** asks to track them.

## Hooks

- **Do not** bypass Git hooks with `--no-verify` / `-n` unless the user **explicitly** asks to skip hooks for that commit.

